Pembrolizumab Monotherapy for Advanced Non-Small Cell Lung Cancer
Pembrolizumab is a monoclonal antibody that targets PD-L1, a protein that is expressed on the surface of cancer cells. Pembrolizumab blocks the interaction of PD-L1 with its receptor on cancer cells, leading to cancer cell death. Pembrolizumab is administered every 3 weeks, during which patients are monitored for survival.
Pembrolizumab is approved for patients with advanced non-small cell lung cancer who have already tried chemotherapy.
Advanced non-small cell lung cancer is a type of lung cancer that is more advanced than others. It means that the cancer has spread to other parts of the body and is harder to treat.
Pembrolizumab is the first drug in a new class of medicines called immunotherapies. Immunotherapies work by targeting proteins on the surface of cancer cells that help them grow and divide.
Pembrolizumab is the first drug in a new class of medicines called checkpoint inhibitors.

Cerebral palsy (CP) is a neuromotor disorder that affects the developing child. It is a common condition that requires comprehensive care to ensure the affected child attains the maximum potential. Children with cerebral palsy often experience motor impairments that can affect their ability to participate in daily activities and impact their quality of life. These impairments can range from mild to severe and can affect the ability to walk, sit, stand, and perform fine motor skills. They might also experience difficulties with oral intake, bowel and bladder control, and social interaction. Cerebral palsy can also affect the childs ability to perform gross motor functions such as running, jumping, and climbing. In addition, children with cerebral palsy might experience skeletal abnormalities, such as scoliosis or foot deformities. These issues can lead to further health complications, such as respiratory problems or the need for assistive devices, and should be monitored closely. This is a summary of the key issues relating to the use of CFTR modulators in the treatment of cystic fibrosis.
Cystic fibrosis is a genetic disorder which affects the respiratory, digestive and reproductive systems. It is caused by a defect in the CFTR gene which leads to a reduction in the production of the protein that controls the movement of salt and water in the body.
CFTR modulators are drugs which can help to increase the production of the protein, and improve the function of the digestive and reproductive systems. They work by stimulating the CFTR gene, and have been shown to improve lung function and reduce inflammation in people with cystic fibrosis.
There are two CFTR modulators which have been licensed for use in the UK - ivacaftor and tezacaftor. They act in a similar way, but there is currently no evidence to suggest that one is more effective than the other. Both are administered by injection into the vein, and are usually given every four to six weeks.
CFTR modulators have been shown to improve lung function and reduce inflammation in people with cystic fibrosis. They have also been shown to have other benefits, such as improved BMI and reduced rate of hospitalisation.
People with cystic fibrosis may have other medical conditions, such as inflammatory bowel disease or liver disease. It is important to discuss any other medical conditions with a doctor before starting treatment with CFTR modulators.
There is currently no evidence to suggest that CFTR modulators increase the life expectancy of people with cystic fibrosis, but they have been shown to improve quality of life and reduce the need for hospitalisation.
CFTR modulators are not a cure for cystic fibrosis, and it is important to note that they do not correct the genetic defect which causes the condition.
There is currently no evidence to suggest that CFTR modulators are safe for use in children, but they have been shown to be generally well tolerated in adults.
It is important to note that CFTR modulators are not a treatment for cystic fibrosis, and that they should only be used in addition to the ongoing medical treatment which is required for people with the condition.

| Secondary Purpose: To compare the effects of nursing care on comfort and sleep quality in intensive care patients.

| Exclusion Criteria: No history of sedative use.

| Other: No history of sedative use.

Cardiac sarcoidosis is a rare disease that affects the heart. It is characterized by the formation of granulomas in the myocardium, which are areas of abnormal growth of cells that look like grains of sand. These granulomas can cause the heart to become enlarged and heavy, and may interfere with its normal function.
